as a volume list and verify the check catches a missing required volume by temporarily defining one. This satisfies the test requirement.\n\nHere's my implementation plan:\n\n1. **Add `validateDeploymentManifest` to `pkg/controller/istiocsr/deployments.go`** — checks for `istiocsrContainerName` container and a defined set of required volumes (empty for now but the mechanism is in place, and I'll add it checking a const `requiredVolumes` slice).\n\nActually, the simplest and most correct approach for the task: define a `validateDeploymentManifest` that checks both container name and volumes from a const list, exactly like trustmanager. The test demonstrates it works by constructing broken manifests. Let me just be practical and check the container name and keep a list of required volume names (even if empty, the test can verify the logic by constructing scenarios).\n\nBut the test must \"confirm the guard fires when passed a deliberately broken manifest (missing container or missing volume).\" For the volume test to actually fire, the validator must check for at least one volume name. Let me see if there's any sensible volume to require...\n\nLooking at the bindata manifest one more time — it has NO volumes. The only volumes are added at runtime by `updateVolumeWithIssuerCA`. So there's no static volume to validate. However, I can make the design future-proof and the test meaningful by having the function accept/check required volumes. For the \"missing volume\" test, I'll test the code path directly by constructing a deployment that should have a volume and verifying the error.\n\nLet me just implement it cleanly. Here's my final plan:\n\n1. Add `validateDeploymentManifest` function that checks:\n   - Container named `istiocsrContainerName` exists\n   - All volumes in a `requiredVolumes` slice exist (the slice can be empty in production but the code path is tested)\n   \n2. Call it from `getDeploymentObject` right after decoding the deployment, before any mutations\